<subSubSection id="15DE5FE0FF8CEF4FFF42FD3BFDD6FC1D" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF8CEF4FFF42FD3BFA9BFD11" blockId="36.[151,1437,581,933]" box="[199,1326,654,681]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF8CEF4FFF42FD3BFEE7FD10" bold="true" box="[199,338,654,680]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Comments:</emphasis>
The species is easily found on the grasses and bushes of open areas within the preserve.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF8CEF4FFF42FD07FD71FCAC" blockId="36.[151,1437,581,933]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF8CEF4FFF42FD07FEEEFD74" bold="true" box="[199,347,690,716]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Bioacoustics</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="C5FF10EEFF8CEF4FFEE9FD07FE40FD74" box="[364,501,690,716]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1919,1943]" captionTargetBox="[208,1382,190,1887]" captionTargetId="figure-29@38.[200,1387,181,1895]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 18. Calling songs of the species of Phaneropterini species from the ParNa Iguaçu. A–F: Anaulacomera argentina; C–E: Grammadera albida; F–H: Grammadera steinbachi. A, C and D: sonogram of one echeme, two and three isolated syllables, respectively; B, D and G: sonogram of a syllable; F, E and H: spectrogram of the respective syllable." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6550097" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6550097/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 18D–F</figureCitation>
): Males stridulate continually during the entire day and night. The calling song is simple, since the emitted syllables are not grouped in echemes. Each syllable presents a gradual increase of intensity until its peak, followed by a gradual decrescendo.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF8CEF4FFF42FCAAFDDCFC80" blockId="36.[151,1437,581,933]" box="[199,617,798,825]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF8CEF4FFF42FCAAFE1EFC80" box="[199,427,798,824]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Dominant frequency</emphasis>
: 28,9 ± 0,3 kHz.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF8CEF4FFF42FCF7FE45FCE4" blockId="36.[151,1437,581,933]" box="[199,496,834,861]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF8CEF4FFF42FCF7FEF5FCE4" box="[199,320,834,860]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Bandwidth</emphasis>
: 4,7 ± 0,8 kHz.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF8CEF4FFF42FCD2FD90FC39" blockId="36.[151,1437,581,933]" box="[199,549,870,897]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF8CEF4FFF42FCD2FE9BFC38" box="[199,302,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Duration</emphasis>
: Syllable: 6 ± 0,8 ms.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF8CEF4FFF42FC3EFDD6FC1D" blockId="36.[151,1437,581,933]" box="[199,611,906,933]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF8CEF4FFF42FC3EFEEAFC1C" box="[199,351,906,932]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Mute interval</emphasis>
: Syllable: 0,7 ± 
<geoCoordinate id="38F06AACFF8CEF4FFD9CFC3FFDEBFC1D" box="[537,606,906,933]" degrees="0, 17" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" precision="555" value="-0.17">0,17 s</geoCoordinate>
.
</paragraph>
